definitions.text:
taverns; Three Taverns, the name of a village or town on the Appian
                  Way, about thirty-three miles from Rome.
antelope; Tabitha, a Christian woman at Joppa.
I endure severe hardship, am harassed, complain.
a talent of silver or gold
a talent of silver or gold.
a store-chamber, secret chamber, closet; a granary, barn.

order, (a) regular arrangement, (b) appointed succession, (c) position,
                  rank.
humble, lowly, in position or spirit (in a good sense).
I make or bring low, humble, humiliate; pass: I am humbled.
I disturb, agitate, stir up, trouble.
Tarsus, the capital of the Roman province Cilicia.
I thrust down to Tartarus or Gehenna.
(a) I assign, arrange, (b) I determine; mid: I appoint.
most swiftly, most quickly, as quickly as possible.
a wall, especially of a city.
I bear children, beget, rear a family.
child bearing, the rearing of a family.
I bring up children, rear young.

perfect, (a) complete in all its parts, (b) full grown, of full age,
                  (c) specially of the completeness of Christian character.

(a) as a course, a race, or the like: I complete, finish (b) as of time
                  or prediction: I accomplish, (c) I make perfect; pass: I am perfected.
(a) I end, finish, (b) I fulfill, accomplish, (c) I pay.

(a) an end, (b) event or issue, (c) the principal end, aim, purpose,
                  (d) a tax.
Tertius, who wrote the Epistle to the Romans at Paul's dictation.

Tertullus, a barrister acting as professional prosecutor of Paul at
                  Caesarea.
of the fourth day, four days since.
a quaternion, a group of four soldiers.
of four months, a period of four months.
I rule over as a tetrarch
I rule over as a tetrarch.
a tetrarch, ruler over a fourth part of a region.
I reduce to ashes, consume, destroy.
I make liquid; pass: I melt (away).
I keep, guard, observe, watch over.

Tiberias, a town in Galilee on the western border of the sea called
                  after it.
Tiberius, the second Roman emperor (died A.D. 37).
I put, place, lay, set, fix, establish.
I bear, bring forth, produce, beget, yield.
Timaeus, father of the blind beggar Bartimaeus.
I value at a price, honor
(a) I value at a price, estimate, (b) I honor, reverence.
Timothy, a Christian of Lystra, helper of Paul.
Timon, one of the seven original deacons at Jerusalem.
any one, some one, a certain one or thing.

Titus, a Greek Christian, helper of Paul, perhaps also brother of
                  Luke.
consequently, therefore, well then, so then.
indeed now, therefore, accordingly, well then.
of this kind, such, such as follows.
I dare, endure, am bold, have courage, make up the mind.
more boldly, more freely, with more confidence.
a place, region, seat; an opportunity.
so great, so large, so long, so many.
on the contrary, on the other hand.
a table for food or business

a table, (a) for food or banqueting, (b) for money-changing or
                  business.
I am laid bare, laid open
I am laid bare, laid open.
Trachonitis, the north-east of the territory beyond Jordan.
I feed, nourish; I bring up, rear, provide for.
I run, exercise myself, make progress.
a worn path, beaten way, road, highway.
having three stories, the third story
having three stories; subst: the third story.
(a) way, manner, (b) manner of life, character.
I endure the ways of, put up with.
Trophimus, a Christian of Ephesus in Asia.
the track of a wheel, a path
the track of a wheel, a path.
a hole, the eye of a needle
a hole; the eye of a needle.
Tryphaena, a Christian woman in Rome.
I live a luxurious life, live self-indulgently.

Tryphosa, a Christian woman in Rome, perhaps a sister of
                  Tryphaena.
Troas, a harbor city of Mysia.
Trogyllium, a promontory somewhat to the south of Ephesus.
I eat, partake of a meal.

(a) gen: I obtain, (b) absol: I chance, happen; ordinary, everyday, it
                  may chance, perhaps.
I torture, break on the wheel
I torture, break on the wheel, beat to death.

(originally: the mark of a blow, then a stamp struck by a die), (a) a
                  figure; a copy, image, (b) a pattern, model, (c) a type, prefiguring something or
                  somebody.
I beat, strike, wound, inflict punishment
I beat, strike, wound, inflict punishment.
Tyrannus, an inhabitant of Ephesus, probably a rhetorician.
I agitate or disturb in mind
I agitate or disturb in mind, trouble.
a Tyrian, an inhabitant of Tyre.
Tyre, an ancient city, the capital of Phoenicia.
I make blind, physically or mentally.
I puff up, make haughty; pass: I am puffed up, am haughty.
Tychicus, a Christian of the Roman province Asia.
